{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487010"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:53:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:53:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"230"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/230"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.29,0.36,0.28,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"230"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47395"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/230"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"230"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32129"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"266"},{"type":"tags","id":"1201"},{"type":"tags","id":"4785"},{"type":"tags","id":"9139"},{"type":"tags","id":"9259"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"981"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11521"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12580"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35578"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46030"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47395"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of a painful swelling around his anus. This followed an episode of constipation and straining at stool. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears uncomfortable. His vital signs are within normal limits. Perianal examination is seen below (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Haemorrhoid artery ligation","Incision and evacuation of haematoma","Acute haemorrhoidectomy","Pain relief and elective haemorrhoidectomy","Excision and wound debridement"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a prolapsed and thrombosed internal haemorrhoid. There is ulceration over one of the prolapsed haemorrhoids. Thrombosis is a serious complication of internal haemorrhoids. Patients with thrombosed or strangulated haemorrhoids present with severely painful and irreducible, incarcerated haemorrhoids, which may become necrotic. Acutely thrombosed internal haemorrhoids can be extremely painful and distressing. Given the patient has had only 24 hours of symptoms, the most effective way of giving this patient rapid relief from his symptoms is to perform an \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute haemorrhoidectomy\u003C/strong\u003E, especially due the overlying skin ulceration. Unless the surrounding tissue is necrotic, mucosa and anoderm should be preserved to prevent post-operative anal stricture. Delaying active intervention with \u003Cstrong\u003Epain relief and elective haemorrhoidectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would just add to the patient\u0027s misery. However, if the patient presents with \u0026gt;72 hours of symptoms (as commonly occurs) the oedema and pain has likely already peaked, in which case conservative management is best and acute haemorrhoidectomy at this stage will cause more pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemorrhoid artery ligation\u003C/strong\u003E is a less invasive surgical alternative to conventional haemorrhoidectomy for patients with less severe haemorrhoids. It is not appropriate for prolapsed, thrombosed haemorrhoids. \u003Cstrong\u003EExcision and wound debridement\u003C/strong\u003E would not deal with the underlying problem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf this was a perianal haematoma, then \u003Cstrong\u003Eincision and evacuation of the haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Prolapsed and thrombosed haemorrhoids presenting within 72 hours are best treated by prompt haemorrhoidectomy."],"references":["Lohsiriwat V. Treatment of hemorrhoids: A coloproctologist\u0027s view. World J Gastroenterol. 2015;21(31):9245-52. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4541377/","Sun Z, Migaly J. Review of Hemorrhoid Disease: Presentation and Management. Clin Colon Rectal Surg. 2016 Mar;29(1):22-9. Available online: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4755769/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32129"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"230"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17235"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17235"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cc64f91e-66d2-4d78-93c6-f5740a8ef80a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cc64f91e-66d2-4d78-93c6-f5740a8ef80a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32129","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32129"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-22T23:28:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-29T09:09:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"230"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47395"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47: